#  Modules Implemented : 

## 1. D Flip-Flop

### Description
The D Flip-Flop is a positive edge-triggered sequential circuit that stores one bit of data. During every rising edge of
the clock signal, the output **Q** takes the value present at the **D** input.

### Applications

- Registers
- Memory Elements
- Shift Registers
- Synchronizers
- Data Storage

---

## 2. JK Flip-Flop

### Description
The JK Flip-Flop removes the invalid state of the SR Flip-Flop. Depending on the values of **J** and **K**, it 
can Hold, Reset, Set, or Toggle the output.

### Truth Table

| J | K | Q(next)  |
|---|---|----------|
| 0 | 0 | No Change|
| 0 | 1 |  Reset   |
| 1 | 0 |   Set    |
| 1 | 1 |  Toggle  |

### Applications
- Counters
- Frequency Divider
- Control Circuits
- Sequential Logic

---
## 3. 4-Bit Register

### Description
A 4-bit Register stores four bits simultaneously. The input data is loaded into the register on the positive edge 
of the clock and remains stored until the next clock edge.

### Features
- Parallel Data Storage
- Positive Edge Triggered
- 4-bit Output

### Applications
- CPU Registers
- Temporary Data Storage
- Buffers
- Digital Systems

---

## 4. 4-Bit Counter

### Description
The 4-bit synchronous counter increments its count on every rising edge of the clock. After reaching **1111 (F)**, 
it automatically rolls over to **0000**.

### Counting Sequence
```
0000
0001
0010
0011
....
1110
1111
0000
```

### Applications
- Digital Clocks
- Timers
- Event Counters
- Frequency Division

---

#  Simulation Results :

Behavioral simulations were performed using **Xilinx Vivado**.

The simulation waveforms confirm:
- ✔ Correct D Flip-Flop operation
- ✔ JK Hold, Reset, Set and Toggle operations
- ✔ Proper Register data storage
- ✔ Correct Counter sequence from 0 to F
- ✔ Clock-synchronized sequential behavior

